Jayavarman VIII — Iconoclasm, Kingship, and Angkor’s Last Stone - Varro|https://lucasvarro.com/blogs/angkorpedia/jayavarman-viii|the long, compassionate reign of Jayavarman VII, stone had softened. Faces multiplied, roads reached outward like veins, hospitals and rest houses gathered the vulnerable into the body of the state. The empire had learned a new  ...    Where his predecessors had allowed the empire’s sacred centre to fracture and reform around compassion, Jayavarman VIII  ...    History remembers him as an iconoclast. Stone Buddhas were defaced, bodhisattvas stripped of their serenity, serene  ...    Within the capital, however, restraint was harder to maintain. The Buddhist images that had softened Angkor’s gaze were altered, removed, or erased. At the Bayon, the Buddha of the central sanctuary was broken and cast down. Yet even this act feels less like rage than anxiety: a ruler attempting to reassert coherence over a world that had grown too plural, too fluid, too compassionate to obey a single axis. Jayavarman VIII was not merely undoing his predecessors; he was trying to re-tighten the mandala. 
